ilding a nationwide system of roads and drew attention to his idea with the march to Washington. In Coxey's Crusade for Jobs, Jerry Prout recounts Coxey's story and adds depth and context by focusing on the reporters who were embedded in the march. Their fascinating depictions of life on the road occupied the headlines and front pages of America's newspapers for more than a month, turning the spectacle into a serialized drama. These accounts humanized the idea of unemployment and helped Americans realize that in a new industrial economy, unemployment was not going away and the unemployed deserved attention. This unique study will appeal to scholars and students interested in the Gilded Age and US and labor history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLaborzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aUnemployedzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aUnemploymentzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking classzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aHumanities & Human Rights. 4aLabor History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  apopulism, laissez-faire market, Masillon Ohio, Jacob Coxey.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175690040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501756900423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501756900/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK